THOUGHT: The crash asserts because VPTransformState::get is asked for a vector value of a VPReplicateRecipe that only produced scalar lanes (no packed vector), likely due to isUniform or shouldPack=false paths. In VPReplicateRecipe::execute, when IsUniform we only scalarize lane 0 and return without setting a vector value. Later, someone requests a vector and hits the assert. A safe fix is to ensure that for uniform replicated instructions under vector VF, we broadcast the scalar result to a vector using CreateVectorSplat and register it with State.set(this, Vec). I will open more of VPReplicateRecipe::execute to implement a vector splat for the IsUniform path after scalarizing lane 0.

```bash
applypatch << 'EOF'
*** Begin Patch
*** Update File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp
@@
   if (IsUniform) {
     // Uniform within VL means we need to generate lane 0.
-    State.ILV->scalarizeInstruction(UI, this, VPLane(0), State);
-    return;
+    State.ILV->scalarizeInstruction(UI, this, VPLane(0), State);
+    // If VF > 1, some users may request a vector value for this recipe. As this
+    // is uniform, materialize a splat vector from the scalar lane-0 value so
+    // VPTransformState::get can return a vector without asserting.
+    if (State.VF.isVector()) {
+      Value *Scalar = State.get(this, VPLane(0));
+      Value *Vec = State.Builder.CreateVectorSplat(State.VF, Scalar, "uniform.splat");
+      State.set(this, Vec);
+    }
+    return;
   }
*** End Patch
EOF
```

