THOUGHT: The crash occurs in VPTransformState::get when a non-uniform operand is requested for a non-first lane but only scalar values are recorded (no vector value). To make the code robust, I'll add a fallback in VPTransformState::get: if no vector exists and the specific lane scalar isn't available, but the first-lane scalar exists, return that scalar. This mirrors uniform behavior and prevents the assertion while keeping semantics reasonable for cases where only a single scalar was materialized.

```bash
sed -i '231,238{s/assert(hasVectorValue(Def));/if (!hasVectorValue(Def)) {
    if (hasScalarValue(Def, Lane))
      return Data.VPV2Scalars[Def][Lane.mapToCacheIndex(VF)];
    if (hasScalarValue(Def, VPLane::getFirstLane()))
      return Data.VPV2Scalars[Def][0];
  }
  assert(hasVectorValue(Def));/}' llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlan.cpp
```

